Solution. If $\varepsilon>0-$ is an arbitrarily large number, then

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{2 n^{2}-3 n+2}{n+2}>\varepsilon \Leftrightarrow & \left\{\begin{array}{cc}
2 n^{2}-3 n+2 & \frac{n+2}{2 n-7} \\
\frac{2 n^{2}+4 n}{-7 n+2} & \\
\frac{-7 n-14}{16}
\end{array}\right\} \Leftrightarrow \\
& \Leftrightarrow 2 n-7+\frac{16}{n+2}>\varepsilon \Leftarrow 2 n-7>\varepsilon \Leftrightarrow n>\frac{7+\varepsilon}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Let $N=\left[\frac{7+\varepsilon}{2}\right]$ (for example, if $\varepsilon=10^{6}$, then we take $N=\left[\frac{10^{6}+7}{2}\right]=$ $=500003)$. If $n>N$, then $\frac{2 n^{2}-3 n+2}{n+2}>\varepsilon$. This is consistent with the fact that $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \frac{2 n^{2}-3 n+2}{n+2}=+\infty$.

