Solution. Let's divide the integration region $x \in [0, \infty)$ into two subregions $x \in [0,1]$ and $x \in [1, \infty)$. Then

$$
I=\int_{0}^{1} \frac{d x}{\left(1+x^{2}\right)\left(1+x^{a}\right)}+\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{d x}{\left(1+x^{2}\right)\left(1+x^{a}\right)}=I_{1}+I_{2}
$$

In the first integral, we perform the substitution

$$
\begin{gathered}
z=\frac{1}{x}, d x=-\frac{d z}{z^{2}}, x \in [0,1] \Rightarrow z \in [1, \infty) \\
I_{1}=\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{d z}{\left(1+z^{2}\right)\left(1+z^{-a}\right)} \\
I=I_{1}+I_{2}=\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{d z}{\left(1+z^{2}\right)\left(1+z^{-a}\right)}+\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{d x}{\left(1+x^{2}\right)\left(1+x^{a}\right)}=
\end{gathered}
$$

from here

$$
=\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{d x}{1+x^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{1+x^{a}}+\frac{x^{a}}{1+x^{a}}\right)=\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{d x}{1+x^{2}}
$$

The last expression no longer depends on $a$. Let's compute the resulting integral

$$
\begin{gathered}
I=\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{d x}{1+x^{2}}=\left.\lim _{b \rightarrow \infty} \operatorname{arctg} x\right|_{1} ^{b}=\lim _{b \rightarrow \infty}(\operatorname{arctg} b-\operatorname{arctg} 1)= \\
=\frac{\pi}{2}-\frac{\pi}{4}=\frac{\pi}{4}
\end{gathered}
$$

Solution. In Example 4.5, the convergence of the series of inverse squares $b_{n}=\frac{1}{n^{2}}$ was proven. In our case, $a_{n}=\frac{100^{n}}{n!}$. Let's form the ratios of subsequent terms to previous ones:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_{n}} & =\frac{100^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}: \frac{100^{n}}{n!}=\frac{100}{n+1} \\
\frac{b_{n+1}}{b_{n}} & =\frac{1}{(n+1)^{2}}: \frac{1}{n^{2}}=\frac{n^{2}}{(n+1)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Choose $n_{0}$ such that for all $n \geqslant n_{0}$ the inequality

$$
\frac{100}{(n+1)} \leqslant \frac{n^{2}}{(n+1)^{2}}, \text { i.e., } 100 \leqslant \frac{n^{2}}{n+1}
$$

is satisfied. Solving the last inequality, we see that $n_{0}$ can be taken, for example, as 105. Thus, $\forall n \geqslant 105$ we have:

$$
\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_{n}} \leqslant \frac{b_{n+1}}{b_{n}}
$$

Therefore, by Theorem 4.7, the series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{100^{n}}{n!}$ converges.

